'''Audacious Inquiry''' (Ai) is a [[health information technology]] company providing [[cloud-based]] software to enable secure exchange of actionable data among healthcare organizations. The company also delivers IT consulting and advisory services to advance healthcare [[interoperability]] and public health.
Audacious Inquiry assisted [[Johns Hopkins Medicine]], [[University of Maryland Medical System]], [[MedStar Health]], [[Erickson Living]], and the [[Maryland Department of Health]] in the establishment of [[Chesapeake Regional Information System for our Patients]] (CRISP), which is widely considered one of the most successful health information exchange organizations in the United States.<ref name=UP_AND_COMER_AI_2017>{{Citation | title = Up-and-Comers 2017: Audacious Inquiry’s Bold Goals for Health Information Exchange | url = https://www.healthcare-informatics.com/article/hie/and-comers-2017-audacious-inquiry-s-bold-goals-health-information-exchange | year = 2017 | author = Health Informatics - David Raths | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref> Ai developed the Encounter Notification Service, an event-driven model for standards-based [[health information exchange]], in partnership with CRISP. Ai now supports or directly operates similar, "connected healthcare" efforts in several other US states and regions.
Audacious Inquiry developed the [https://sequoiaproject.org/pulse/ Patient Unified Lookup System for Emergencies (PULSE)] and now partners with the Sequoia Project to enable PULSE as a nationwide disaster response solution.<ref name=PULSE_ModernHealthcare)>{{Citation | title = Modern Healthcare Story on PULSE and HIE to support disaster response | url = https://www.modernhealthcare.com/article/20180914/news/180919917 | year = 2018 | author = Modern Healthcare - Rachel Z. Arndt | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref> In 2017 and 2018, providers used PULSE during the California wildfires.<ref name=PULSE_Wired)>{{Citation | title = Wired Magazine Story on PULSE and Electronic Health Record Access During Disasters | url = https://www.wired.com/story/harvey-evacuees-leave-their-belongings-and-health-records-behind/ | year = 2017 | author = Wired Magazine - Megan Moltini | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref>
Audacious Inquiry is a certified [[B Corporation]].<ref name=BBJ_BCORPS_2016>{{Citation | title = Here's why 'B Corps' could help Baltimore spur economic development | url = https://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2016/07/19/heres-why-b-corps-could-help-baltimore-spur.html | year = 2016 | author = Baltimore Business Journal - Jonathan Munshaw | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref> In 2017, Ai received outside investment from [[ABS Capital Partners]].<ref name=Sun_ABS_Ai>{{Citation | title = Baltimore health technology firm receives first outside investment | url = https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-audacious-inquiry-abs-20180122-story.html | year = 2018 | author = Baltimore Sun - Christopher Dinsmore | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref> Ai graduated from the [http://www.hceda.org/who-we-are/maryland-center-for-entrepreneurship/ Maryland Center for Entrepreneurship], and the company is headquartered in the BWtech Research Park on the campus of [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]].<ref name=BmoreMedia2010>{{Citation | title = BMore Media Reports AI move to BWTech Research park at UMBC | url = http://www.bmoremedia.com/devnews/audaciousinquiry081010.aspx | year = 2010 | author = BMore Media - Julekha Dash | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref>
== History ==
Audacious Inquiry was founded in 2004. The company endured the [[Great Recession]],<ref name=BBJ2009>{{Citation | title = Audacious Inquiry Recognized in the Recession Survival Issue of Baltimore Business Journal | url = http://baltimore.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/2009/08/31/story7.html | year = 2009 | author = Baltimore Business Journal - Daniel Sernovitz | accessdate = 2010-10-10 }}</ref> and managed some growth through that period.<ref name=NPR2009>{{Citation | title = Audacious Inquiry CEO a guest on NPR for discussion about creating jobs coming out of the recession | url = https://www.npr.org/2011/09/08/140297253/can-new-federal-policies-get-employers-hiring | year = 2011 | author = NPR - Talk of the Nation transcript | accessdate = 2018-11-14 }}</ref>
