'''Nägele's obliquity''' is the presentation of the anterior [[parietal bone]] to the [[birth canal]] during [[vaginal delivery]] with the [[biparietal diameter]] being oblique to the brim of the [[pelvis]].<ref name="thefreedictionary">{{cite web|url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/Naegele+obliquity|publisher=medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com|title=Naegele obliquity &#124; definition of Naegele obliquity by Medical dictionary|accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref> The synonym for this presentation is anterior asynclitism.<ref name="drugs">{{cite web|url=https://www.drugs.com/dict/anterior-asynclitism.html|publisher=drugs.com|title=Anterior asynclitism definition &#124; Drugs.com|accessdate=2017-04-11}}</ref> It was first described in 1777 by German Karl Nägele.<ref>{{cite book | page = 694 | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=bYI6AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA624&lpg=PA624&dq=N%C3%A4gele's+obliquity&source=bl&ots=qvYyQJbOgs&sig=93tgMaEO5MjNdEQqrfs-6v01Gtk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjT3O-ylp3TAhUD9GMKHbf6C4oQ6AEIQjAJ#v=onepage&q=N%C3%A4gele's%20obliquity&f=false
|title =The American Illustrated Medical Dictionary  | isbn = | publisher= W.B. Saunders Company | date = 1916 | postscript = ; digitized by The Ohio State University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | page = 1191 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=B4wtDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1191&dq=N%C3%A4gele's+obliquity&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpgKjFmJ3TAhVdVWMKHRjyCekQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=N%C3%A4gele's%20obliquity&f=false | title = Mosby's Medical Dictionary | date = 2016 | isbn = 9780323414258 }}</ref>

